## APP Mass Analysis of `itemsBasePremium`

**Current code:**
```typescript
const itemsBasePremium = (items: Item[]): number => {
  const components = items.filter((i) => COMPONENT_TYPES.has(i.type));
  const others = items.filter((i) => !COMPONENT_TYPES.has(i.type));
  const byType: Record<string, number> = {};
  for (const c of components) {
    byType[c.type] = (byType[c.type] ?? 0) + 1;
  }
  let componentsBase = 0;
  for (const [type, count] of Object.entries(byType)) {
    if (count === COMPONENT_BLOCK_SIZE) {
      componentsBase += COMPONENT_BLOCK_PRICE;
    } else {
      componentsBase += count * BASE_PREMIUM[type];
    }
  }
  return componentsBase + sum(others.map(itemBasePremium));
};
```

**Mass count:**
- Constants: 0, 1 = 2
- Bindings: items, components, others, byType, i (×2), c, c.type (×3), componentsBase, type, count = ~15
- Invocations: filter (×2), has (×2), !, for-of access, ??, Object.entries, ===, +=, *, BASE_PREMIUM[], sum, map, + = ~14 invocations × 2 = 28
- Conditionals: if/else = 4
- Loops: 2 for-loops = 10
- Assignments: byType[c.type] = ..., let componentsBase = 0, componentsBase += (×2) = 4 assignments × 6 = 24

**Total Mass: ~83**

The function has two for-loops with assignments — high mass. I can refactor to functional style.

